'''Critical Military Studies''' is a new academic sub-discipline which brings [[critical theory]] to the study of [[military institutions]] and practices.<ref>http://www.criticalmilitarystudies.org/</ref> It intersects with many academic disciplines, such as [[international relations]], political science, [[gender studies]], human geography and anthropology.<ref>http://www.criticalmilitarystudies.org/</ref> Academic conferences in 2013 and 2014 have included panels on Critical Military Studies.<ref>http://everydaymilitarism.wordpress.com/category/critical-military-studies/</ref><ref>http://www.isanet.org/Portals/0/Documents/ResearchGrants/2013%20Workshop%20Grants/Brown_workshop_final_report.pdf</ref> The sub-discipline also has a new academic journal published by Taylor and Francis.<ref>http://www.tandfonline.com/loi/rcms20#.VBraFfldUeE</ref> Scholarship on Critical Military Studies includes issues such as military recruitment <ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/23269995.2014.909243 | volume=4 | title=Recruitment, counter-recruitment and critical military studies | journal=Global Discourse | pages=244–262}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/23269995.2014.922278 | volume=4 | title=Critical studies of the military or critical military studies: a response to Rech on recruitment and counter-recruitment | journal=Global Discourse | pages=263–266}}</ref> and military landscapes.<ref>http://phg.sagepub.com/content/early/2013/06/25/0309132513493219.abstract</ref> Critical Military Studies is particularly concerned with how understandings of gender and sexuality shape military practices and research on the military.<ref>http://www.isanet.org/Portals/0/Documents/ResearchGrants/2013%20Workshop%20Grants/Brown_workshop_final_report.pdf</ref>

